ce:section.ce:para:
Aiming to produce theranostic tools able to be used for both diagnosis and therapy, CDs were analyzed for their spectroscopic and photoluminescence features to be used as a tracing agent. To this, an addition of a therapeutic molecule (curcumin) was planned to be encapsulated together inside liposomes. Additionally, anti-CD44 antibodies were grafted to the liposome surface to create a targeting system. The initial characterization of the different liposome formulations was performed using visual observations (Fig. 2
                        A), UV–Vis spectroscopy (Fig. 2B), and fluorimetric analysis (Fig. 2C). Free curcumin demonstrated a maximum absorbance at 427.2 nm which was similarly observed in the other CUR-containing liposomes. CDs and CD liposomes provided similar observation with a maximum absorbance at 335 nm (Fig. 2B). Furthermore, CD liposomes and F3 were analyzed for their fluorescent characteristics. Liposome formulations were analyzed according to the characteristics determined for the synthesized free CDs. The observations showed that curcumin induced a shift in the fluorescence characteristics of the CDs (Fig. 2C). This effect has been recently attributed to the reaction of CDs and curcumin. Curcumin has been shown to lose fluorescence capacity in aqueous solutions [30]. Additionally, quantum dots and carbon dots have been used as curcumin sensors due to fluorescence quenching via fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET) [31,32]. On the other hand, the determination of the size, PDI, and zeta-potential of the vesicles was performed via DLS (Table 2
                        ).
